panels.description:
How many responses do we return with errors?

There will always be some latent errors, but a rising statistic may be worrisome. This is particularly useful in incidents.
panels.title: HTTP Error response rate

panels.description:
How many responses do we return with errors?

There will always be some latent errors, but a rising statistic may be worrisome. This is particularly interesting in incidents.

By default, this panel is limited to 15 minute intervals. This is because most deployments have low traffic volume, so anything lower makes little sense.
panels.title: HTTP Error response ratio

panels.description:
Out of all requests, how many of them are cancelled by the caller OR time out on our end as configured?

This is generally not particularly worrisome, but if it is very high for a very long period of time, it may be worth looking into. Consider raising the timeouts, for example.

By default, this panel is limited to 15 minute intervals. This is because most deployments have low traffic volume, so anything lower makes little sense.
panels.title: HTTP request timeout ratio

panels.description:
How many HTTP requests do we get?

This panel is not intended to be worrisome. Use it for costs estimations and understanding what's going on during incidents.
panels.title: HTTP request rate

panels.description:
How many HTTP requests do we get?

This panel is not intended to be worrisome. Use it for costs estimations and understanding what's going on during incidents.
panels.title: HTTP request rate with status

panels.description:
This is how many total requests we have in flight. This is essentially the request queue.

Only expensive calls are listed here; that means, metrics, healthchecks, etc. are not listed. Render requests are listed.

It is fine for this to spike every so often, but a growing number should be seen as worrisome. This is best used together with the response status panels.
panels.title: HTTP requests in flight

panels.description:
How long does a request take to complete, from start to finish? This only includes `^GET /render(/csv)?$`

Note that this will include times that come from timeouts.

This panel is not intended to be worrisome. Use it during incidents.
panels.title: HTTP response latency

Timeouts are not considered errors here.

panels.title: HTTP response latency: Errors (4xx, 5xx)

panels.description:
How long does a request take to complete, from start to finish? This only includes `^GET /render(/csv)?$`

This only considers timeouts.

This panel is not intended to be worrisome. Use it during incidents.
panels.title: HTTP response latency: Timeouts (408)

panels.description: How long do each of the functions take to complete?
panels.title: BrowserService function durations (p95)

panels.description: How long does each action in render functions take?

targets.expr: max by(action) (histogram_quantile(0.95, sum by(le, action) (rate(browser_action_duration_bucket{job=~"$promjob", unit="seconds"}[$__rate_interval]))))

panels.title: Browser Render action durations (p95)

panels.description: How many active browsers are there?
panels.title: Active browsers over time

panels.description:
The max of any process is the maximum memory any Chromium process has used.

The peak memory usage over time is how much memory the average process uses. It uses a slow-moving average with decay, thus it takes many requests to move the needle significantly.
panels.title: Chromium memory usage over time

panels.description:
This is the peak memory usage reported by each process on every request.

This is not intended to be worrisome, rather to help debug performance problems.
panels.title: Chromium memory usage per request

panels.description: How large is a response from each MIME type?

targets.expr: avg by(mime_type) (histogram_quantile(0.99, sum by(le, mime_type) (rate(browser_request_size_bucket{job=~"$promjob", unit="bytes"}[$__rate_interval]))))

panels.title: Browser response sizes (p99)
